circunistances and occurrences ; which nHist depend, in* 
fioite ways, on foregoing acts of their wills ; which are oe« 
casioned by innumerable things that happen in the coarse 
of their lives, in which their own, and their neighbors' be- 
havior, roust have a hand an infinite number of ways. 
And as the volitions ofothers must be so many ways con* 
cerned in the conception and birtli of such men ; so, no less 
in their preservation, and circumstances of life, their par* 
ticular determinations and actions, on which the great 
revolutions they were the occasion of, depended. As, for 
