162 GOO CratTAIflLr ronXKftOWM fART II. 

pear reason to convince us, ftiat he could not^ with any 
absolute certainty, foresee even these. As to the Jirst, 
namely, tilings done by the immediate and extraordinary 
interposiiion of God's po^'er, these cannot be foreseeUy 
unless it can be foreseen when there shall be occasion for 
•ilch extraordintiry interposition. And that cSnnot be fore- 
aeen, unless the state of the moral world can be foreseen. 
For whenever God thus iriterposes, it is with regard lo the 
state of the moral world requiring such divine interposition. 
Thus, God could not certainly foresee the universal de- 
luge, the calling of Abraham, the destruction of Sodom and 
Gomorrah, the plagues on Egypt, and Israel's redemption 
out of it, the expelling the seven nations of Canaan, and 
the bringing brael into that land ; for these all are repre- 
sented as connected with things belonging to the state of 
the moral world. Nor can God foreknow the most pro- 
per and convenient time of ihe day of judgment and gen- 
eral conflagration ; for that chiefly depends on the course 
and state of things in the moral world. 

Nor, secondly^ can we on this supposition reasonably 
think, that God can certainly foresee what things shall 
come to pass, in the course of things, in the natural and 
material world, even those which in an ordinary state of 
things might be calculated by a good astronomer. For 
the moral world is the end of the natural world ; and the 
oourse of things in the former is undoubtedly subonlinate 
to God's designs with respect to the latter. Therefore be 
iias seen cause, from regard to the state of things in the 
moral world, extraordinarily to interpose, to interrupt and 
lay an arrest on the course of things in the natural world ; 
and even in the greater wheels of its motion, even so as 
to stop the sun in its course. And unless be can foresee 



