I HAVE already considered how Dr. Whitby insists 
upon it, that a freedom, not only from coaction, but ne- 
cessity, is requisite either to virtue or vice^ praise or dis- 
praise^ reward or punishment. He also insists on the 
same freedom as absolutely requisite to a person's being 
the subject of a laWy of precepts y or prohibitions ; in the 
book before mentioned, (pp. 301, 314, 328, 339, 340, 
341, 342, 347, 361, 373, 410.) And of promises and 
threntenings, (pp. 298, 301, 305, 31 1, 339, 340, 363.) 
And as requisite to a state of trials (p. 297, etc.) 

Now, therefore, with an eye to these things, I would 
inquire into the moral conduct and practices of our Lord 
Jesus Christ, which he exhibited in his human nature 
here in his state of humiliation. And firsts I would show, 
that his holy behavior was necessary ; or that it was im- 
possible it should be otherwise than that be should behave 
Inmself holily, and that he should be perfectly holy in 
each individual act of his life. And secondly, that his 
holy behavior was properly the nature of virtue^ and was 



