absdute and most perfect right to do what be wills, with- 
out subjection (o any superior authority^ or any derivation 
of authority from any other, or limitation by any distinct in- 
dependent authority, either superior, equa), or inferior ; he 
being tiiehead ofall dominion, and fountain of all authority ; 
and also without restraint -by any obligaiion, implying ei- 
ther subjection, derivation, or dependence, or proper limi- 
tation. (3) That his mil is supreme, underived, and in- 
dependent on anything without himself; being in every- 
thing detennined by his own counsel, having no other rule 
but his own wisdom ; his will not being subject to, or re- 
strained by the will of any other, and other wills being per- 
fectly subject to his. (4) That his msdoniy which de- 
termines his will, is supreme, perfect, underived, self-suffi- 
cient, and independent ; so that it may be said, as in Isai- 
