tioD is only bjr some difierence. And if there be no 
varieiy aniong proposed obftcts ofckoic^y then there is no* 
op^portunity for variety of choiccj or difference of vdeter-^ 
mioation. For that deleriniiiation . of a thing, which if. 
not different in any respect, is not a different detennina- 
tioiiy but the same» That this is no quibble^ may appear 
more fully anon. 

Tlie arguments to prove that the Most High, in some 
instances, chooses to do one thing rather than another, 
where the things themselves are perfectly without differ- 
ence, are two. 

1. That the various parts of infinite time and space^ 
absolutely considered, are perfectly alike,, and do not differ 
at a4i one from another; and that therefore, when God 
determined to create the world in such a part of in- 
