wdvt unda supervenU undmm* But when we imaigine this, we faaey 
that the minutes are things separately existing. This is tlie common 
notion ; and yet it is a manifest prejudice. Time is nothing but the 
existence of created successive beings, and eternity the necessary 
existence of the Deity. Therefore, if this necessary 0eing hath no 
change or succession in his nature, his esistenee must of course be 
unsuccessive. We seem to commit a double oversight in this case ; 
firstf we find succession in the necessary nature and existence of the 
Deity himself; which is wrong, if the reasoning above be conclusiTe. 
And then we ascribe this succession to eternity, considered abstraet- 
edly from the Eternal Being ; and suppose it, one knows not what, 
a thing subsisting by itself, and flowing one minute after another. 
This is the work of pure imagination, and contrary to the reality of 
things. Hence the common metaphorical expressions : Time runs 
m^acBy let vs lay lu/ld on ike present mtnvte, and the like. The phir 
losophers themselves mislead us by their illustration. They compare 
eternity to the motion of a point running on for ever, and making a 
traceless infinite line. Here the point is supposed a thing actually 
subsisting, representing the present minute ; and then they ascribe 
motion or succession to it : that is, they ascrilie motion to a mere non- 
entity, to illustrate to us a successive eternity, made up of finite suc> 
eessive parts. — If once we allow an all-perfect Mind, which hath an 
eternal immutable, and infinite comprehension of all things always, 
(and allow it we miist),^ the distinction of past and future vanishes 
with respect to such a Mind. In a word, if we proceed step by step, 
fts above, the eternity or existence of the Deity will appear to be 
wUtB interminabitis, tota, simul etperfecta possessio; how much soever 
this may have been a parodox hitherto." — Inquiry into the MUurt tf 
tfts Human Soul, toL ii. pp. 409—411. £dit. 3. 



